% Automatisch generiert — Thema: Death Penalty
% arg/1 Fakten
arg(pro82).  % [pro] On the contrary, sometimes defendants insist on execution.
arg(pro15).  % [pro] Deserved punishment protects society morally by restoring the just order.
arg(pro15b).  % [pro] Deserved punishment makes the wrongdoer pay a price equivalent to the harm the wrongdoer has done.
arg(pro4).  % [pro] The framers of the Constitution clearly believed that capital punishment was an acceptable means of protecting society from wicked dissolute men.
arg(pro4b).  % [pro] Thomas Jefferson liked to talk about capital punishment.
arg(pro95).  % [pro] It has been proven that these killers reoffend repeatedly.
arg(pro36).  % [pro] If the criminal knows that the justice system will not stop at putting the criminal to death, then the system appears more draconian to the criminal.
arg(pro32).  % [pro] Retribution or "an eye for an eye" honors the victim.
arg(pro32b).  % [pro] Retribution helps console grieving families.
arg(pro32c).  % [pro] Retribution ensures that perpetrators of heinous crimes never have an opportunity to cause future tragedy.
arg(pro29).  % [pro] Capital punishment is still a threat to the criminal.
arg(con36).  % [con] The sad thing about the death penalty is that innocence is proven after the execution has been carried out.
arg(con189).  % [con] Once an inmate is executed, nothing can be done to make amends if a mistake has been made.
arg(con27).  % [con] Thus, for every seven people executed, we have found one person on death row who never should have been convicted.
arg(con174).  % [con] As the saying goes, "Capital punishment means that those without capital get the punishment."
arg(con190).  % [con] Is it fair that someone should be murdered just because they were unlucky enough to be born with a brain defect?
arg(con229).  % [con] A recent study by Columbia University Law School found that two thirds of all capital trials contained serious errors.
arg(con140).  % [con] Allowing executions sanctions killing as a form of pay‑back.

% att/2 Fakten  (Dung 1995 — binär; Typ/conf aus LLM-Kandidaten als Kommentar)
att(pro82, pro29).  % [undermining] conf=80 — Shows that some criminals desire execution, undermining the premise that the death penalty is a threat to criminals
att(con229, pro15).  % [undermining] conf=80 — The study’s claim of widespread trial errors attacks the premise that deserved punishment can be justly applied.
att(con140, pro15).  % [rebuttal] conf=85 — Sanctioning killing as pay‑back directly contradicts the claim that deserved punishment morally restores order.
att(pro36, pro15b).  % [undermining] conf=70 — Pro36 suggests death may not be sufficient deterrent, challenging the premise that deserved punishment fully compensates for harm.
att(pro36, pro15).  % [undermining] conf=80 — pro36 questions the moral adequacy of death as final punishment, challenging pro15's premise that deserved punishment restores moral order
att(con36, pro15).  % [undermining] conf=90 — con36 shows executions can be wrongful, undermining the premise that punishment is deserved and morally protective
att(con189, pro15).  % [undermining] conf=90 — con189 argues no remedy after a mistaken execution, challenging the moral justification of pro15
att(con27, pro15).  % [undermining] conf=85 — con27 provides evidence of wrongful convictions, weakening pro15’s claim of deserved punishment
att(con174, pro15).  % [undermining] conf=80 — con174 highlights socioeconomic bias, attacking the fairness premise behind pro15’s deserved‑punishment claim
att(con190, pro15).  % [undermining] conf=85 — con190 questions the fairness of executing individuals with brain defects, undermining the moral legitimacy of pro15’s argument
att(con36, pro15b).  % [undermining] conf=90 — Con36 highlights the risk of executing innocent people, challenging the premise that the punished individual is truly the wrongdoer.
att(con189, pro15b).  % [undermining] conf=90 — Con189 points out the irreversibility of execution, undermining the premise that deserved punishment can be correctly applied.
att(con27, pro15b).  % [undermining] conf=90 — Con27 provides evidence of wrongful convictions, attacking the premise that the punished person is the actual wrongdoer.
att(con174, pro15b).  % [undermining] conf=80 — Con174 argues that capital punishment disproportionately affects the poor, challenging the fairness premise of deserved punishment.
att(con190, pro15b).  % [undermining] conf=80 — Con190 questions the fairness of executing individuals with brain defects, undermining the premise that punishment is based solely on harm caused.
att(con229, pro15b).  % [undermining] conf=90 — Con229 cites systematic trial errors, attacking the premise that the convicted are correctly identified as wrongdoers.
att(con140, pro15b).  % [undermining] conf=70 — Con140 frames executions as sanctioned pay‑back killing, challenging the moral premise that such punishment is a just equivalent to harm.
att(con36, pro4).  % [rebuttal] conf=78 — Con36 argues the death penalty is unacceptable because innocent people may be executed, contradicting pro4’s claim of acceptability.
att(con189, pro4).  % [rebuttal] conf=80 — Con189 states that wrongful execution makes the penalty irrevocable, opposing pro4’s stance that it is an acceptable measure.
att(con27, pro4).  % [rebuttal] conf=82 — Con27 highlights frequent wrongful convictions, directly challenging the acceptability asserted in pro4.
att(con174, pro4).  % [rebuttal] conf=75 — Con174 frames capital punishment as unjust punishment of the poor, contradicting pro4’s claim of its acceptability.
att(con190, pro4).  % [rebuttal] conf=77 — Con190 questions the fairness of executing individuals with brain defects, opposing the notion that death penalty is appropriate.
att(con229, pro4).  % [rebuttal] conf=85 — Con229 cites systematic trial errors, undermining the legitimacy of the death penalty endorsed by pro4.
att(con140, pro4).  % [rebuttal] conf=80 — Con140 argues that executions legitimize revenge killing, directly conflicting with pro4’s claim of acceptability.
att(pro36, pro95).  % [rebuttal] conf=70 — B argues the death penalty is insufficient and draconian, contradicting A’s justification that it prevents repeat offenses.
